## ⚡ Strategy

### Approach
To successfully achieve the project objectives within the development timeframe, the execution strategy is broken down into four progressive, linear phases. This structured approach ensures that hardware bugs are caught early before ordering fabrication, and software complexity is built on top of verified electrical baselines.

#### Phase 1: Schematic Capture & Footprint Auditing
* **Action Items:** Finalize the net connections for the low-side MOSFET driver, flyback diode, and current-limiting gate resistor. Verify that the physical pin pitches of the microcontroller female headers, IMU, and OLED display footprints match the physical components exactly.
* **Feasibility Check:** Completed. Form factors are standardized on a $2.54\text{mm}$ pitch for simple hand-soldering and testing.

#### Phase 2: PCB Layout & Design Rule Verification
* **Action Items:** Route power rails ($+5\text{V}$, $+3\text{V}3$) with thick traces ($\ge 0.5\text{mm}$) to handle higher current paths safely. Enclose the entire layout with a dedicated, continuous bottom layer copper ground plane (`B.Cu`) to suppress inductive switching noise from the motor. Run the KiCad Design Rules Checker (DRC) to fix all board boundary conflicts, edge clearances, and short circuits.
* **Feasibility Check:** Completed. Ground plane short-circuit errors resolved via a proper Filled Zone polygon.

#### Phase 3: Hardware Bring-Up (Cold & Warm Testing)
* **Action Items:** Perform a "Cold Test" using a multimeter in continuity mode immediately after soldering to ensure 0-ohm paths exist only on valid nets (verifying no power-to-ground shorts). Perform a "Warm Test" by applying power to the unpopulated board to measure and verify stable $+5.0\text{V}$ and $+3.3\text{V}$ outputs on the component sockets.
* **Feasibility Check:** Planned immediately upon physical board delivery to prevent damaging expensive processing ICs.

#### Phase 4: Embedded Firmware & Algorithmic Calibration
* **Action Items:** Write the basic peripheral drivers to confirm stable I2C bus communications with the IMU and OLED display. Implement the complementary filter algorithm to blend accelerometer and gyroscope data into a clean thigh-angle estimation stream. Build the 4-stage software state machine (Standing, Descent, Bottom/Valid, Ascent) and fine-tune the calibration thresholds during live test squat sets.
* **Feasibility Check:** Highly achievable; development will utilize a modular codebase to easily isolate and debug algorithmic filtering lag.

### Target Audience
Because RepSense is a specialized personal development project, the target audience is unique:
* **Primary User (Self):** A strength-training athlete looking for an objective, automated, real-time depth cue during heavy barbell squats without needing a training partner or video review.
* **Secondary Audience (Open Source/Engineering Community):** Hardware hobbyists, embedded systems developers, and powerlifters on GitHub who want to replicate, modify, or scale the wearable platform for their own training style or research.

### Measurement
Progress and success will be tracked quantitatively using the following baselines:
* **Hardware Manufacturing Readiness:** Achieve a layout state with **0 errors and 0 warnings** under the KiCad Design Rules Checker (DRC).
* **Firmware Latency Baseline:** The time delay between crossing the physical squat depth angle and the haptic motor pulsing must be **$\le 50\text{ms}$** to ensure the lifter receives the cue at the exact bottom of the rep.
* **Algorithmic Accuracy:** The complementary filter must maintain an angle estimation drift of **$< 2^{\circ}$** over a standard 5-repetition working set when compared against visual video analysis benchmarks.
